**Erdős Problem #443: Common Products k(m-k) and l(n-l)**

For m, n ≥ 1, consider the product sets:
- A_m = { k(m-k) : 1 ≤ k ≤ m/2 }
- B_n = { l(n-l) : 1 ≤ l ≤ n/2 }

Questions: Can |A_m ∩ B_n| be arbitrarily large? Is it ≤ (mn)^{o(1)}?

Both answered YES by Hegyvári (2025) and Cambie.

**hegyvari_upper_bound:**

When m > n: |A_m ∩ B_n| ≤ m^{O(1/log log m)}

This is the key upper bound. The exponent 1/log log m → 0 very slowly, giving subpolynomial growth.
